ISO 639-1 (2-character) code for the interface language to be used at the payment device and in transaction status messages.
This is an optional value that lets the CUSS application suggest a language to use when performing the payment transaction.
The payment subsystem could use this value to adjust prompts displayed on the payment terminal screen or the language on the
preformatted receipt data. This value could be set in response to a prior language selection by the kiosk application user as
part of the overall kiosk transaction. The payment system may override this setting once a language value is read from the card
itself as part of the transaction.

Optional common use terminal/application operational parameters, allowing the CUSS application to indicate more specific values related
to the payment transaction for tracking and reconciliation purposes. If the CUSS application does not supply any values, the CUSS platform
may provide appropriate values to the payment subsystem depending on what data fields that subsystem requires.
Common use kiosk/terminal/station identifier. May be reported on cardholder or reconciliation statements for informational purposes.

Agent/cashier (or pseudo-cashier) identifier. May be reported on cardholder or reconciliation statements for informational purposes.
Some payment solutions may require this, but the component will synthesize a value if one is required but none is explicitly provided.

Airline/merchant order, receipt or ticket reference number. May be reported on cardholder or reconciliation statements
for informational purposes.
Details of previously acquired pre-authorization being finalized by this post-authorization.

The information in the itinerary block is optional and lets the CUSS application specific additional tracking and
reconciliation data for the payment transaction, relating specifically to an airline transaction itinerary.
The CUSS platform provider may mandate that this information be provided with all transactions.
This requirement will be established during the negotiation and configuration phase of the initial deployment of
payment capability for an airline. It is anticipated that the CUSS platform itself will not store or make use of this
information. Instead, it will be forwarded to the payment solution for back-end reconciliation purposes.

Descriptive billing information. This optional value lets the CUSS application suggest a value that will
appear on the kiosk application users payment summary (monthly bill, etc.) as an extended description of
the transaction. The value may or may not appear on the customers bill depending on the capabilities of
the airport and customers banking systems. Long data may be truncated. The platform may also be used as
an additional tracking mechanism for other systems such as aggregator and reconciliation infrastructure.

The non-approval-reason-code and referral values are not standard and will vary between payment systems. These values are likely
useful for logging and reconciliation purposes and would not likely be exposed to the kiosk user or affect the business logic of
the kiosk transaction.

What modes of payment are supported by the payment terminal or requested by the application. The application requests a
particular mode of payment in its setup() request parameters. The auto-commit feature indicates whether or not the application
wishes to perform a manual commit at the end of a successful transaction. The pre-authorization feature indicates whether the
pre-authorization/post-authorization payment model is supported.

Special or proprietary payment parameters that can be provided by the CUSS application when requesting the payment,
and/or returned by the payment subsystem upon conclusion of the transaction. These are optional values. This container
is included in the schema to allow certain legacy payment protocols to be migrated to use the new payment interface.
It also allows for flexibility for future payment industry requirements that may affect common use or airline payment.

*NOT_APPLICABLE:* None of the codes below apply (e.g. state change to AVAILABLE or ACTIVE)

*OUT_OF_SERVICE_BHS:* The Baggage Handling System is not available

Virtual component state codes

*READY:* Component is ready to receive and execute any directives
*BUSY:* Indicates any component activity (e.g. reading/writing) that has been invoked
*UNVAILABLE:* Error condition that requires manual intervention

Virtual component types with the following semantics...

*CAPTURE:* Captures the document in a secured bin
*DISPENSER:* Offer the document to the user or the user
*FEEDER:* Offer the document from a feeder to another component (userless)
*DATA_INPUT:* Inbound data transfer (e.g. digital input)
*DATA_OUTPUT:* Outbound data transfer (e.g. illumination device)
*USER_INPUT:* Inbound user data transfer (e.g. baggage scale )
*USER_OUTPUT:* Outbound user data transfer (e.g. screen)
*MEDIA_INPUT:* Components used for reading from media (e.g. bar-code reader)
*MEDIA_OUTPUT:* Components used for writing to media (e.g. receipt printer)
*STORAGE:* Reading/writing from/to storage (e.g. harddisk)
*DISPLAY:* Handle a display (eg. the CUSS device screen)
*NETWORK:* Handle network access
*BAGGAGE_SCALE:* Represent a stand-alone baggage scale
*INSERTION_BELT:* Insert/return position of a conveyor system
*VERIFICATION_BELT:* Verification position of a conveyor system
*PARKING_BELT:* Parking position of a conveyor system
*ANNOUNCEMENT:* Audible output component allowing applications to use SSML
*APPLICATION:* Used to query the state and/or characteristics of a CUSS application

Device Types describe how applications handle the device and how to advise users

*NON_APPLICABLE_DEVICE_TYPE:* Device does not fit in any category
*PRINT:* Device can print documents
*READ:* Device can read documents
*MOTORIZED:* Device can move in and out a document (e.g. cards)
*DIP:* User has to dip in and remove a document (e.g. cards or passports)
*SWIPE:* User has to swipe the document or card
*CONTACTLESS:* Device can read a document from a (usually short) distance
*HANDHELD:* Device can scan bar codes and and needs to be handled manually
*INSERT:* Documents have to be inserted into the device
*DISPENSE:* Device can dispense a document to the user or another component
*CAPTURE:* Device can retract documents or cards
*CONVEYOR:* Device can move baggage back and forth
*SCALE:* Device can weigh items
*CAMERA:* Device can take pictures
*FLATBED:* Device can scan documents
*CHIP_AND_PIN:* Device is a Chip & PIN device / payment device
*EXTERNAL:* Device is not contained in the CUSS device
*BIOMETRICS:* Device is a biometrics device / interface
*ASSISTIVE:* Device can assist users with disabilities
*ILLUMINATION:* Device represents a light
*DISPLAY:* Device represents a display (e.g. a touch screen)

Severity categorization for the various events

WARNING:* Abnormal situation occurs, but manual intervention is not needed

Relations for all events

*SOLICITED:* Event relates to an application request
*UNSOLICITED:* Sent by the platform because of any internal change, not related to any request.

Categorization of publicity for the various events

*PRIVATE:* Private events are sent as a solicited response only to those applications having requested an action on the platform
*PUBLIC:* Public events indicate e.g. a state change of a component that is of interest for all applications
*PLATFORM:* Sent internally between CUSS Application Manager, CLA, and the Component Interface

Messagecodes related to system, applications and platform directives/devices.

*OK:* Device is ready or interface call did not generate an error. - *public (private for solicited events)*
*CANCELLED:* Interface call was cancelled. - *private*
*WRONG_SYSTEM_STATE:* The system or component is in the wrong state to process the call. - *private + platform*
*WRONG_APPLICATION_STATE:* The application is in the wrong state to process the call. - *private + platform*
*OUT_OF_SEQUENCE:* Function has been called out of sequence. (e.g. calling send() before enable()) - *private*
*TIMEOUT:* Function call timed out. - *private (directive related)*
*FORMAT_ERROR:* Error detected in format of data used with send() or setup(). - *private + platform (platform only for output classes)*
*LENGTH_ERROR:* Data stream provided for send()/setup() is incomplete. - *private + platform (platform only for output classes)*

*HARDWARE_ERROR:* An error caused by hardware malfunction makes the component UNAVAILABLE. - *public*

*NOT_RESPONDING:* Device or application is connected but not responding or not ready. - *public*

*KILL_TIMEOUT:* Application exceeded the max. time for responding to the session timeout. - *private + platform (application related)*

Platform directives name definitions and descriptions.

*Please note:* In contrast to earlier CUSS versions applications are now responsible for tracking and handling the time and timeouts for any directive that may require longer execution. Applications shall use the cancel directive to terminate a too long pending call.

*platform_environment:* This is the **second directive** to be issued by the application to get basic information on the specific CUSS Platform implementation.
*platform_components:* This directive returns a list of all the implemented components, their characteristics and their object identifiers. This allows the application to check whether all the components that it requires are implemented or not.
*platform_applications_staterequest:* This directive is used by the application to request a state change from CUSS Application Manager, which will change the application state if request is approved.
*platform_applications_transferrequest:* This directive is used by the application to request an application transfer from the CUSS Application Manager.
*platform_applications_acknowledge_accessible:* An application confirms with this directive that it has switched to accessible mode after being activated by the CUSS application manager for the accessible mode.
*peripherals_announcement_play:* Requests that an SSML formatted text to be spoken immediately. - Directive requires component identifier and the XML formatted text to be spoken.
*peripherals_announcement_pause:* Temporarily suspends any play back currently in progress. - Directive requires component identifier.
*peripherals_announcement_resume:* Resumes any paused play back currently in progress. - Directive requires component identifier.
*peripherals_announcement_stop:* Stops any play back currently in progress. - Directive requires component identifier.
*peripherals_cancel:* Cancels all currently executed and queued directives on this component at the time of issuing this directive. - Directive requires component identifier.
*peripherals_query:* Returns the current state/status of the virtual component. - Directive requires component identifier.
*peripherals_send:* Sends data from the application to the component. - Directive requires component identifier.
*peripherals_setup:* Set up the profile/context of the virtual component and prepare it for application usage. - Directive requires component identifier.
*peripherals_userpresent_enable:* Make the virtual component available for the user (e.g. enable a reader device for a document insertion). - Directive requires component identifier.
*peripherals_userpresent_disable:* Make the virtual component unavailable for the user (e.g. disable a reader device from a document insertion). - Directive requires component identifier.
*peripherals_userpresent_offer:* Offers a document or a processed item from the virtual component to the user or to another component. - Directive requires component identifier.
*peripherals_conveyors_forward:* Moves a bag to the next position on the conveyor or to the airports collector belt. - Directive requires component identifier.
*peripherals_conveyors_backward:* Moves a bag back to the previous position on the conveyor or back to the user. - Directive requires component identifier.
*peripherals_conveyors_process:* Examine and/or process the bag currently on a belt component to get baggage data like weight, dimensions, LPNs, RFID, and similar. - Directive requires component identifier.
